WEBVTT

00:00:02.402 --> 00:00:04.805
[person]
For me, WW is the Super Bowl.

00:00:04.838 --> 00:00:06.406
[person]
You can feel the energy.

00:00:06.440 --> 00:00:08.208
[person]
It's like really deep insights

00:00:08.242 --> 00:00:10.244
of what it feels like
being a developer.

00:00:14.948 --> 00:00:16.683
[person]
Really?

00:00:16.717 --> 00:00:17.751
[person]
Wow.

00:00:17.784 --> 00:00:19.820
[laughs]

00:00:22.489 --> 00:00:23.957
[person]
Okay, we open on black.

00:00:24.925 --> 00:00:27.528
The curtain slowly opens.

00:00:27.561 --> 00:00:30.497
Have a DeLorean on the stage.

00:00:30.531 --> 00:00:32.666
Tim Cook gets out
of that DeLorean,

00:00:32.699 --> 00:00:36.103
showing the phone's
flux capacitor.

00:00:36.136 --> 00:00:38.906
[person] I would probably
not start there.

00:00:38.939 --> 00:00:41.775
I think it's kind of geeky.

00:00:41.808 --> 00:00:42.943
[person] Cut!

00:00:42.976 --> 00:00:44.278
[person]
Are we going to go again?

00:00:44.311 --> 00:00:46.380
[person] So we open on black.

00:00:46.413 --> 00:00:48.448
[person]
Does it have to be black?

00:00:48.482 --> 00:00:49.983
[person]
It doesn't have to be black.

00:00:50.017 --> 00:00:51.151
[both] It could be yellow.

00:00:51.185 --> 00:00:53.587
[person] Now my mind goes into,
like, a cartoon.

00:00:53.620 --> 00:00:55.989
[person] Imagine someone
on their computer,

00:00:56.023 --> 00:00:57.391
you know, they have an idea.

00:00:57.424 --> 00:00:58.992
And, like, they push,
like, enter,

00:00:59.026 --> 00:01:03.163
or some red button
and it goes out to the world.

00:01:03.197 --> 00:01:06.266
And then all of a sudden,
there's like millions of people

00:01:06.300 --> 00:01:08.535
around the globe
that get to experience

00:01:08.569 --> 00:01:10.304
the thing that you've made.

00:01:10.337 --> 00:01:12.673
Are you actually able
to do all this?

00:01:12.706 --> 00:01:13.707
[person] Um...

00:01:13.740 --> 00:01:14.842
[record scratch]

00:01:16.543 --> 00:01:18.111
[person]
Maybe the title of the film

00:01:18.145 --> 00:01:21.348
should be
"Our Journey Into Tomorrow."

00:01:21.381 --> 00:01:25.452
I see a little girl
in an endless white room.

00:01:27.120 --> 00:01:28.956
She meets Craig Federighi.

00:01:28.989 --> 00:01:30.591
[Craig] Hi.

00:01:30.624 --> 00:01:31.859
[person] But we don't see him.

00:01:31.892 --> 00:01:33.093
We just hear his voice.

00:01:33.126 --> 00:01:34.261
[Craig] Not cool.

00:01:34.294 --> 00:01:36.029
[echoing]

00:01:36.063 --> 00:01:37.364
[person] Now she's older.

00:01:37.397 --> 00:01:39.900
And dressed for work.

00:01:39.933 --> 00:01:41.435
[person] There has to be action
at this point

00:01:41.468 --> 00:01:42.769
or, like, some sort of drama.

00:01:42.803 --> 00:01:45.672
She goes to work and discovers
something catastrophic.

00:01:45.706 --> 00:01:46.940
Someone says...

00:01:46.974 --> 00:01:48.909
[person] We have a bug.

00:01:48.942 --> 00:01:51.378
[person] So she comes in

00:01:51.411 --> 00:01:53.480
and pounds on the keyboard.

00:01:53.514 --> 00:01:56.483
[dramatic music]

00:01:56.517 --> 00:01:58.118
And the bug is fixed.

00:01:58.151 --> 00:01:59.186
[cheering]

00:01:59.219 --> 00:02:00.787
Yeah, it's like a musical.

00:02:00.821 --> 00:02:01.655
[person] Musical?

00:02:01.688 --> 00:02:04.558
[person]
Yeah, The Bug, But A Musical.

00:02:04.591 --> 00:02:06.226
[music]

00:02:10.797 --> 00:02:12.165
[music continues]

00:02:15.202 --> 00:02:18.205
[music continues]

00:02:26.046 --> 00:02:26.880
[person] Wait a minute.

00:02:26.914 --> 00:02:30.951
Why not make arena rock of WW?

00:02:30.984 --> 00:02:33.987
[music]

00:02:37.858 --> 00:02:41.195
There wouldn't be
any pyro usually.

00:02:41.228 --> 00:02:42.429
But I think, why not?

00:02:42.462 --> 00:02:44.064
Pyro is fun.

00:02:47.167 --> 00:02:49.069
[person]
Do you think it would work?

00:02:49.102 --> 00:02:50.604
[person] Uh, you won't know
if you don't try.

00:02:50.637 --> 00:02:53.607
[music continues]

00:02:53.640 --> 00:02:56.610
[chanting]

00:02:56.643 --> 00:02:59.646
[cheering]

00:03:11.258 --> 00:03:12.559
[Tim] Good morning.

00:03:12.593 --> 00:03:15.128
And welcome to WWDC.

00:03:15.162 --> 00:03:17.531
It's so wonderful to see
so many familiar faces

00:03:17.564 --> 00:03:19.333
with us today.

00:03:19.366 --> 00:03:22.402
We're excited to share
our latest technologies with you

00:03:22.436 --> 00:03:24.171
and with the incredible
community

00:03:24.204 --> 00:03:27.341
of millions of Apple developers
around the world.

00:03:27.374 --> 00:03:29.710
Your creativity
and groundbreaking apps

00:03:29.743 --> 00:03:32.679
continue to deliver new
and meaningful ways

00:03:32.713 --> 00:03:34.915
to enrich people's lives.

00:03:34.948 --> 00:03:37.050
We applaud
the extraordinary work

00:03:37.084 --> 00:03:38.118
you've been able to do

00:03:38.151 --> 00:03:40.187
throughout
this challenging time.

00:03:40.220 --> 00:03:43.357
Last year's WWDC
was our most inclusive

00:03:43.390 --> 00:03:45.893
and most watched
developer conference ever,

00:03:45.926 --> 00:03:48.795
with nearly 25 million viewers.

00:03:48.829 --> 00:03:51.598
It was exciting to have
so many people join us

00:03:51.632 --> 00:03:55.035
and to see the impact it had
on new Apple developers

00:03:55.068 --> 00:03:58.305
as we broadened our audience,
welcoming more people

00:03:58.338 --> 00:04:00.841
from more places
around the world.

00:04:01.608 --> 00:04:03.877
We've continued to look for ways
to help cultivate

00:04:03.911 --> 00:04:05.979
the next generation
of developers

00:04:06.013 --> 00:04:10.217
with an emphasis on those
underrepresented in technology.

00:04:10.250 --> 00:04:13.220
We host entrepreneur camps
for Black and female developers

00:04:13.253 --> 00:04:17.024
to foster the talents
of future industry leaders.

00:04:17.057 --> 00:04:20.427
Our Developer Academies,
including the newest in Detroit,

00:04:20.460 --> 00:04:22.329
prepare the coders of tomorrow

00:04:22.362 --> 00:04:24.932
with valuable tools
and training.

00:04:24.965 --> 00:04:27.868
And Learn to Code offers
an amazing curriculum

00:04:27.901 --> 00:04:31.705
for people to develop new skills
and learn Swift.

00:04:31.738 --> 00:04:34.208
We are committed
to being a force for change

00:04:34.241 --> 00:04:36.743
as we seek to make the world
a better place,

00:04:36.777 --> 00:04:39.680
full of opportunity
for all of us.

00:04:40.647 --> 00:04:43.750
This year, we're bringing you
another online experience

00:04:43.784 --> 00:04:46.887
featuring over 200
in-depth sessions,

00:04:46.920 --> 00:04:49.156
one-to-one labs
with Apple engineers,

00:04:49.189 --> 00:04:50.591
and so much more.

00:04:50.624 --> 00:04:52.392
We'll provide the tools you need

00:04:52.426 --> 00:04:55.896
to continue creating the world's
most innovative apps,

00:04:55.929 --> 00:04:59.433
apps that inspire us
in new ways every day.

00:04:59.466 --> 00:05:01.869
And just like last year's WWDC,

00:05:01.902 --> 00:05:05.706
this entire conference
will be made available for free.

00:05:06.540 --> 00:05:09.576
We've got a lot of exciting news
and breakthrough innovations

00:05:09.610 --> 00:05:11.345
to share with you today.

00:05:11.378 --> 00:05:14.314
So let's get started
by turning it over to Craig

00:05:14.348 --> 00:05:17.551
to tell us what's new in iOS.

00:05:17.584 --> 00:05:18.685
[Craig] Thanks, Tim.

00:05:18.719 --> 00:05:21.822
All right, let's dive right in.

00:05:25.859 --> 00:05:29.530
For many of us, our iPhone
has become indispensable.

00:05:29.563 --> 00:05:32.799
And at the heart of iPhone
is iOS.

00:05:32.833 --> 00:05:36.403
iOS powers the experiences
we've come to rely on.

00:05:36.436 --> 00:05:38.472
This year,
we were inspired to create

00:05:38.505 --> 00:05:42.376
even more meaningful ways
iPhone could help you.

00:05:42.409 --> 00:05:45.012
Our new release is iOS 15.

00:05:45.045 --> 00:05:48.048
It's packed with features
that make the iOS experience

00:05:48.081 --> 00:05:51.451
adapt to and complement
the way you use iPhone,

00:05:51.485 --> 00:05:53.020
whether it's staying connected

00:05:53.053 --> 00:05:55.455
with those
who matter to you most,

00:05:55.489 --> 00:05:58.759
finding the space
to focus without distraction,

00:05:58.792 --> 00:06:01.828
using intelligence to discover
the information you need,

00:06:01.862 --> 00:06:04.665
or exploring
the world around you.

00:06:04.698 --> 00:06:07.000
Let's start off with features
that will let you

00:06:07.034 --> 00:06:10.103
stay connected
in brand-new ways.

00:06:10.137 --> 00:06:13.106
In a year when figuring out
how to get face-to-face

00:06:13.140 --> 00:06:15.142
has felt more essential
than ever,

00:06:15.175 --> 00:06:17.678
we've all found ourselves
using video calling

00:06:17.711 --> 00:06:19.313
for just about everything,

00:06:19.346 --> 00:06:22.316
and when it comes
to making calls that are easy,

00:06:22.349 --> 00:06:26.320
spontaneous, and connect us
with the people who matter most,

00:06:26.353 --> 00:06:28.856
FaceTime is a standout.

00:06:28.889 --> 00:06:31.058
With its incredibly
intuitive design

00:06:31.091 --> 00:06:33.427
and end-to-end encryption
since day one,

00:06:33.460 --> 00:06:36.997
FaceTime is how we catch up
with friend around the world

00:06:37.030 --> 00:06:40.601
and how we stay close to family
members when we're apart.

00:06:40.634 --> 00:06:42.970
Enjoying these deeply personal
moments over video

00:06:43.003 --> 00:06:45.105
can bring so much joy,

00:06:45.138 --> 00:06:47.307
but it also has its challenges.

00:06:47.341 --> 00:06:49.676
When talking in person,
our brains process

00:06:49.710 --> 00:06:53.280
hundreds of social, auditory
and visual cues.

00:06:53.313 --> 00:06:55.082
When talking on a video call,

00:06:55.115 --> 00:06:57.084
many of those signals
can get lost,

00:06:57.117 --> 00:06:59.052
leaving us feeling drained.

00:06:59.086 --> 00:07:02.122
So this year, we've set out
to make FaceTime calls

00:07:02.155 --> 00:07:05.893
feel more natural,
comfortable, and lifelike.

00:07:05.926 --> 00:07:08.929
First is a feature
that makes FaceTime calls

00:07:08.962 --> 00:07:12.332
sound like you're sitting
in the very same room.

00:07:12.366 --> 00:07:14.501
We're bringing spatial audio
to FaceTime,

00:07:14.535 --> 00:07:17.771
creating a sound field
that helps conversations flow

00:07:17.804 --> 00:07:20.841
as easily as they do
face-to-face.

00:07:20.874 --> 00:07:23.310
Now your friends' voices
are spread out

00:07:23.343 --> 00:07:25.012
to sound like they're coming
from the direction

00:07:25.045 --> 00:07:27.281
in which they're positioned
on the video call,

00:07:27.314 --> 00:07:31.885
making your calls more
comfortable and more natural.

00:07:31.919 --> 00:07:35.489
Next, let's talk about
two powerful new options

00:07:35.522 --> 00:07:37.291
for your microphone.

00:07:37.324 --> 00:07:40.060
The first is voice isolation.

00:07:40.093 --> 00:07:41.395
When you're on a FaceTime call,

00:07:41.428 --> 00:07:44.198
your mic is picking up
a cacophony of sound,

00:07:44.231 --> 00:07:45.732
so in voice isolation,

00:07:45.766 --> 00:07:48.268
machine learning
distinguishes those sounds,

00:07:48.302 --> 00:07:52.606
blocks out the ambient noise,
and prioritizes your voice

00:07:52.639 --> 00:07:55.075
so that it comes through
crystal clear.

00:07:55.108 --> 00:07:56.009
Check it out.

00:07:56.043 --> 00:07:57.444
[person]
I wish I could be there!

00:07:57.477 --> 00:07:59.079
[person] Me too!

00:07:59.112 --> 00:08:01.014
Let me fix this.

00:08:01.949 --> 00:08:03.217
Better, right?

00:08:03.250 --> 00:08:04.218
[person] Yeah.

00:08:04.251 --> 00:08:05.752
[person] Got what she wanted
for her birthday.

00:08:07.688 --> 00:08:08.822
[Craig] Sometimes, though,

00:08:08.856 --> 00:08:11.358
we want every bit of sound
to come through,

00:08:11.391 --> 00:08:14.394
and that's when you switch
to wide spectrum.

00:08:14.428 --> 00:08:16.063
In wide spectrum,
your mic picks up

00:08:16.096 --> 00:08:18.332
an entire symphony's worth
of sound:

00:08:18.365 --> 00:08:21.635
your voice
and everything around you.

00:08:21.668 --> 00:08:25.005
Next, let's turn to video.

00:08:25.038 --> 00:08:27.441
When you want to see
every face in the room,

00:08:27.474 --> 00:08:28.976
you can now turn on grid view,

00:08:29.009 --> 00:08:32.012
giving you another way to view
your group FaceTime calls.

00:08:32.045 --> 00:08:35.015
Here, you see people
in the same size tiles,

00:08:35.048 --> 00:08:38.018
and you'll be able to clearly
identify who's speaking

00:08:38.051 --> 00:08:40.153
while seeing
everyone else's reactions.

00:08:40.187 --> 00:08:42.289
And to make your FaceTime
video capture

00:08:42.322 --> 00:08:46.894
more beautiful than ever,
we're introducing portrait mode,

00:08:46.927 --> 00:08:48.362
where we've taken inspiration

00:08:48.395 --> 00:08:50.697
from iPhone's
stunning portrait photos.

00:08:50.731 --> 00:08:54.034
In FaceTime, portrait mode
blurs the background

00:08:54.067 --> 00:08:57.237
and naturally
puts the focus on you.

00:08:57.271 --> 00:09:00.574
Next, to help you schedule
your FaceTime calls,

00:09:00.607 --> 00:09:03.577
we've created FaceTime links.

00:09:03.610 --> 00:09:06.380
Now you can generate a link
for a FaceTime call

00:09:06.413 --> 00:09:08.715
and share it anywhere.

00:09:08.749 --> 00:09:11.485
It's a terrific way
to plan ahead for a call.

00:09:11.518 --> 00:09:15.055
You can send the FaceTime link
in places like Messages, email,

00:09:15.088 --> 00:09:17.658
WhatsApp,
or jump into Calendar

00:09:17.691 --> 00:09:19.326
and make an event
for your FaceTime call

00:09:19.359 --> 00:09:22.963
so everyone will know exactly
where to meet and when.

00:09:22.996 --> 00:09:25.499
And it's not just Apple devices

00:09:25.532 --> 00:09:27.534
that can use a FaceTime link
to join your call.

00:09:27.568 --> 00:09:30.404
Your friends with Android
and Windows devices

00:09:30.437 --> 00:09:32.439
can use your FaceTime link
to join the call

00:09:32.472 --> 00:09:35.976
right from their browser,
and even on the web,

00:09:36.009 --> 00:09:38.445
FaceTime calls are still
end-to-end encrypted,

00:09:38.478 --> 00:09:41.782
so your privacy
is never compromised.

00:09:41.815 --> 00:09:43.684
Some of our favorite ways
to connect

00:09:43.717 --> 00:09:45.552
involve more than just talking,

00:09:45.586 --> 00:09:47.588
like getting together
for a weekly movie night

00:09:47.621 --> 00:09:49.389
or listening to an album
with a friend

00:09:49.423 --> 00:09:52.059
that brings back
amazing memories.

00:09:52.092 --> 00:09:54.628
We love enjoying
shared experiences,

00:09:54.661 --> 00:09:57.431
and so we built SharePlay.

00:09:57.464 --> 00:10:00.000
SharePlay is a powerful
new set of features

00:09:57.464 --> 00:10:00.000
SharePlay is a powerful
new set of features

00:10:00.033 --> 00:10:01.368
for shared experiences

00:10:01.401 --> 00:10:04.071
that you can enjoy
when you're on a FaceTime call.

00:10:04.104 --> 00:10:07.074
With SharePlay, you can
bring music into your call

00:10:07.107 --> 00:10:10.577
for a shared listening
experience unlike any other,

00:10:10.611 --> 00:10:12.246
watch movies and TV shows

00:10:12.279 --> 00:10:15.983
while having rich, real-time
connection with your friends.

00:10:16.016 --> 00:10:17.718
And share your screen,

00:10:17.751 --> 00:10:19.453
giving you
limitless possibilities

00:10:19.486 --> 00:10:22.923
for bringing apps
right into your FaceTime calls.

00:10:22.956 --> 00:10:24.124
Let me show you how this works,

00:10:24.157 --> 00:10:27.060
starting with
listening together.

00:10:27.094 --> 00:10:29.029
Say you're hanging out
on a FaceTime,

00:10:29.062 --> 00:10:32.032
talking about a new album
that came out over the weekend.

00:10:32.065 --> 00:10:33.000
With SharePlay,

00:10:33.033 --> 00:10:35.903
you could bring that album
right into the conversation.

00:10:35.936 --> 00:10:38.105
When you're on a call,
all you need to do

00:10:38.138 --> 00:10:40.107
is press play in Apple Music,

00:10:40.140 --> 00:10:42.376
and you can choose
to listen together.

00:10:42.409 --> 00:10:45.579
And like magic,
high quality music playback

00:10:45.612 --> 00:10:48.615
will start in sync
for everyone on the call,

00:10:48.649 --> 00:10:50.884
and you're still connected
with FaceTime while listening.

00:10:50.918 --> 00:10:54.721
Everyone on the call
can add songs to a shared queue,

00:10:54.755 --> 00:10:58.659
and shared playback controls
let anyone press play, pause,

00:10:58.692 --> 00:11:00.727
or jump to the next track.

00:11:00.761 --> 00:11:04.498
Now let's check out what
it's like to watch together.

00:11:04.531 --> 00:11:05.666
When you're on
a FaceTime call,

00:11:05.699 --> 00:11:08.569
jump to streaming app
and press play.

00:11:08.602 --> 00:11:09.903
and boom,

00:11:09.937 --> 00:11:13.173
you and your friends
are watching the same video

00:11:13.207 --> 00:11:14.341
totally in sync.

00:11:14.374 --> 00:11:16.343
SharePlay is unlike
any other

00:11:16.376 --> 00:11:18.078
shared content experience
out there

00:11:18.111 --> 00:11:21.014
because it moves fluidly
throughout the whole system.

00:11:21.048 --> 00:11:23.584
Maybe you want to order takeout
while you watch.

00:11:23.617 --> 00:11:25.752
Picture in Picture
lets you see your friends

00:11:25.786 --> 00:11:28.021
and the video
you're enjoying together,

00:11:28.055 --> 00:11:30.390
and controls
are always accessible

00:11:30.424 --> 00:11:31.625
with just a tap.

00:11:31.658 --> 00:11:33.327
And if the group wants
to stay connected

00:11:33.360 --> 00:11:35.429
with no interruptions
to the video's sound,

00:11:35.462 --> 00:11:36.864
you can jump into Messages

00:11:36.897 --> 00:11:39.266
and keep the conversation
going there.

00:11:39.299 --> 00:11:41.969
And when the moment calls
for a bigger screen,

00:11:42.002 --> 00:11:44.771
you can extend the video
to your Apple TV

00:11:44.805 --> 00:11:46.640
and watch it there
while sharing the moment

00:11:46.673 --> 00:11:50.344
with your friends over FaceTime
on your iPhone.

00:11:50.377 --> 00:11:53.547
Even when you're using SharePlay
across multiple devices,

00:11:53.580 --> 00:11:55.916
everyone will remain in sync.

00:11:55.949 --> 00:11:58.151
We wanted to make sure
you have a ton

00:11:58.185 --> 00:12:00.521
of incredible experiences
to share in FaceTime,

00:12:00.554 --> 00:12:03.423
so in addition to Apple Music
and the TV app,

00:12:03.457 --> 00:12:05.192
SharePlay is designed
to work with

00:12:05.225 --> 00:12:08.061
your other favorite apps
and streaming services.

00:12:08.095 --> 00:12:10.864
With an API
built for easy adoption,

00:12:10.898 --> 00:12:14.301
developers can bring their own
apps right into FaceTime.

00:12:14.334 --> 00:12:16.270
And today,
we're so pleased to announce

00:12:16.303 --> 00:12:19.840
that we're already working
with some incredible partners.

00:12:19.873 --> 00:12:23.043
Watch blockbuster movies
with your friends on Disney+,

00:12:23.076 --> 00:12:25.479
and hit TV shows on Hulu.

00:12:25.512 --> 00:12:27.881
Catch originals from HBO Max.

