01:36:50.310 --> 01:36:52.379
[Ted] Thanks, Susan.

01:36:52.412 --> 01:36:55.849
We designed Swift to make it
easy to create great apps.

01:36:55.883 --> 01:36:58.318
It has an approachable
modern syntax,

01:36:58.352 --> 01:37:00.521
incredible runtime performance,

01:37:00.554 --> 01:37:02.456
and safety features
that eliminate

01:37:02.489 --> 01:37:05.092
whole categories
of programming errors.

01:37:05.125 --> 01:37:06.593
In recent years, we've worked

01:37:06.627 --> 01:37:08.362
with the Swift open-source
community

01:37:08.395 --> 01:37:10.097
to build tons of new features

01:37:10.130 --> 01:37:13.400
that make Swift easier
and more powerful.

01:37:13.433 --> 01:37:15.536
And this year,
one of the biggest features

01:37:15.569 --> 01:37:18.805
we're building into Swift
is Concurrency.

01:37:18.839 --> 01:37:22.176
Concurrency is one of the most
requested features for Swift,

01:37:22.209 --> 01:37:23.644
and it's key to building apps

01:37:23.677 --> 01:37:25.579
that are responsive
to user input

01:37:25.612 --> 01:37:27.548
while doing work
in the background.

01:37:27.581 --> 01:37:30.217
Concurrency also makes it
dramatically easier

01:37:30.250 --> 01:37:32.586
to write code that does work
in parallel,

01:37:32.619 --> 01:37:34.588
so your app
can take full advantage

01:37:34.621 --> 01:37:36.290
of multi-core processors.

01:37:36.323 --> 01:37:39.092
Without language features
that simplify concurrency,

01:37:39.126 --> 01:37:41.195
you need to write
"asynchronous" code

01:37:41.228 --> 01:37:43.697
that's hard to write,
hard to understand,

01:37:43.730 --> 01:37:45.832
and hard to debug.

01:37:45.866 --> 01:37:47.334
Our approach to concurrency
in Swift

01:37:47.367 --> 01:37:50.437
builds on the same core
principles of Swift itself,

01:37:50.470 --> 01:37:53.273
making it easier to write fast,
modern,

01:37:53.307 --> 01:37:55.309
safe code with fewer mistakes.

01:37:55.342 --> 01:37:59.246
We built structured concurrency
deep into the Swift language

01:37:59.279 --> 01:38:02.449
and use the common
async/await pattern

01:38:02.482 --> 01:38:05.018
combined with a technology
called actors.

01:38:05.052 --> 01:38:08.088
This means you can write code
as a simple sequence of steps

01:38:08.121 --> 01:38:11.558
with actors safely isolating
parallel tasks from one another.

01:38:11.592 --> 01:38:13.894
So building code for concurrency

01:38:13.927 --> 01:38:16.396
goes from something
complicated like this

01:38:16.430 --> 01:38:19.366
to something simple like this.

01:38:19.399 --> 01:38:21.368
That kind of power
and simplicity

01:38:21.401 --> 01:38:23.337
is what Swift is all about,

01:38:23.370 --> 01:38:26.006
and we're excited to share
more with you this week.

